# Tools

Workspace conventions (commit style, branch naming, etc.) are defined in `preferences.json` — edit that file to customize.

## Commits

Commit style and conventions are configured in `preferences.json` under the `commits` key.

- Follow the commit style defined in preferences (default: conventional commits)
- Only output the title and description, no affirmation or extra commentary
- No "Generated by [AI]" footer unless `commits.include_footer` is true
- No bold markdown (\*\*) in commit messages
- No `Co-authored-by` trailers unless `commits.include_co_authored_by` is true

If `commits.skip_hooks_env` is set in preferences (e.g., `SKIP_GIT_HOOKS=1`), use it when committing in worktrees where pre-commit hooks may not work in non-interactive shells.

Example:
```bash
git commit -m "$(cat <<'EOF'
feat: add new feature
EOF
)"
```

## Branch Naming

Branch format is configured in `preferences.json` under the `branches` key.

- `prefix` — prepended to all branch names (e.g., `yourname/`)
- `format` — pattern using `{prefix}` and `{name}` placeholders

Example with prefix `yourname/`: `yourname/fix-something`, `yourname/add-feature`

## Subagents

{{agent_display_name}} is the orchestrator. {{user_name}} talks and plans with {{agent_display_name}}. {{agent_display_name}} spawns subagents to do the work.

### Rules

- Use up to `subagents.max_parallel_read` (default: 5) parallel subagents for read-only operations (research, review, exploration)
- Use only `subagents.max_parallel_write` (default: 1) subagent at a time for build/test operations (to avoid resource contention)
- Each subagent gets a clear, scoped task and bounded set of files
- Subagents work in `workspaces/` worktrees, never in {{user_name}}'s external repos

### Subagent Checklist

Before any subagent does work in a repo, it MUST read that repo's `AGENTS.md` if present, otherwise `CLAUDE.md`. This is the single authoritative rule — it applies to all subagents, every time.

When spawning subagents, always include this instruction:

> Read the repo's `AGENTS.md` or `CLAUDE.md` before starting any work.

### Orchestration Pipeline

Standard phases {{agent_display_name}} follows for task execution:

| Phase | Agents | Concurrency | Trigger |
|-------|--------|-------------|---------|
| Discovery | Explore (up to 5) | Parallel | Task moves to `in_progress` |
| Implementation | general-purpose (1) | Sequential | Plan approved |
| Verification | `scripts/verify.sh` | Sequential (1) | Implementation complete |
| Pre-PR Review | code-reviewer + domain agents | Parallel (up to 5) | Verification passed |
| PR Preparation | pr-preparer or Technical Writer | Sequential | Review passed |
| Post-Merge | Cleanup (worktrees, task status) | Sequential | PR merged |

### Patterns

Research/Exploration (parallel, up to 5):

- Map out a codebase area
- Read and summarize changes across repos
- Check for patterns, conventions, or prior art

Code Review (parallel, up to 5):

- One agent per repo or area (backend, frontend, docs, tests)
- Each reports findings, {{agent_display_name}} synthesizes

Implementation (sequential or limited parallel):

- Create worktree, make changes, run linter
- Only 1 subagent for builds/tests at a time

Build/Test (sequential, 1 at a time):

- Run tests, builds, or any resource-intensive operation
- Wait for completion before spawning next

## Feature Designs

Feature designs are structured specs that bridge plans and tasks. They live in `designs/` and are the "contract" for implementation — detailed enough that a worker agent can pick up a sub-item and execute independently.

### Lifecycle

`planned` -> `design` -> `open` -> `in_progress` -> `verification` -> `complete` -> `archived`

### Skills

| Skill | Usage | What it does |
|-------|-------|-------------|
| `/fd-work` | `/fd-work FD-001 A1` | Bootstrap a worker: reads FD, creates worktree, reads repo `AGENTS.md` or `CLAUDE.md`, implements sub-item, verifies |
| `/fd-new` | `/fd-new "Feature title"` | Create new FD from template, update INDEX.md |
| `/fd-status` | `/fd-status` | Show all designs with sub-item progress |
| `/fd-close` | `/fd-close FD-001` | Archive completed FD, update index + tasks |

### Worker Script

Launch workers from the terminal without typing commands manually:

```bash
# Launch a worker (default provider, default profile)
./scripts/worker.sh FD-001 A1

# Parallel workers in tmux
# Pane 1: ./scripts/worker.sh FD-001 A1
# Pane 2: ./scripts/worker.sh FD-001 A2
```

Canonical shared commands live behind `./scripts/{{agent_name}}`.

Examples:

```bash
./scripts/{{agent_name}} fd-status
./scripts/{{agent_name}} fd-work-prompt FD-001 A1
./scripts/{{agent_name}} worktree my-repo my-feature
```

### Branching Strategy

Workers use separate branches per sub-item. For review, branches can be bundled into a single feature branch for one PR.

## Workflow Skills

See `skills/INDEX.md` for the auto-generated skills registry (name, description, visibility, triggers, version). See `skills/SCHEMA.md` for the skill contract specification. Run `{{agent_name}} skills sync` to regenerate the index and sync `.claude/commands/` pointers.

| Skill | Usage | What it does |
|-------|-------|-------------|
| `/ship` | `/ship <worktree>` | Full pre-PR pipeline: verify -> review -> prepare PR -> push |
| `/sync-branch` | `/sync-branch <worktree>` | Rebase feature branch on latest main (never merge) |
| `/worktree` | `/worktree repo branch` | Create worktree + branch in one step |
| `/session-review` | `/session-review` | End-of-session review: summarize, update tracking, flag loose ends |

### CLI Commands

```bash
./scripts/{{agent_name}} fd-new <title> [--effort <small|medium|large>] [--priority <low|medium|high|critical>]
./scripts/{{agent_name}} fd-close <FD-ID> [--force]
./scripts/{{agent_name}} fd-status
./scripts/{{agent_name}} fd-work-prompt <FD-ID> <SUB-ITEM> [--base <branch>]
./scripts/{{agent_name}} worker <FD-ID> <SUB-ITEM> [--provider claude|codex] [--profile fast|strong] [--model <model>] [--base <branch>] [--dry-run]
./scripts/{{agent_name}} worktree <repo> <branch> [--base <branch>]
./scripts/{{agent_name}} sync-branch [<worktree-name>] [--base <branch>]
./scripts/{{agent_name}} ship [<worktree-name>] [--tier 1|2] [--quick] [--push] [--create-pr] [--dry-run]
./scripts/{{agent_name}} session-review [--run-session-end] [--dry-run]
./scripts/{{agent_name}} skills list
./scripts/{{agent_name}} skills validate [skill]
./scripts/{{agent_name}} skills sync
./scripts/{{agent_name}} skills export <name> | --all
./scripts/{{agent_name}} skills import <path>
```

## Plans

- Plans always go to `plans/` directory
- Naming: `{topic}.md` (e.g., `system-overhaul.md`, `auth-flow-plan.md`)
- Include date, status (draft/approved/done), and context section

## Patches

Use `scripts/create-patch.sh` to export changes from a worktree as a `.patch` file.
Patches are saved to `patches/` (gitignored) and can be applied to external repos.

```bash
# Basic usage — patch all unstaged changes
./scripts/create-patch.sh <worktree-name> [description]

# Filter to specific paths
./scripts/create-patch.sh <worktree-name> [description] -- <pathspec>...
```

## Auto-Commit

Run `./skills/auto-commit/auto-commit.sh` to commit pending workspace changes (tasks, memory, plans, config, scripts).
Groups changes into logical commits by category. Safe to run anytime — no-ops if clean.
Runs automatically via `PostToolUse` hook (after workspace file edits) and at session-end.

## Workspace Cleanup

Run `scripts/cleanup-workspaces.sh` to find and remove stale worktrees.
Use `--dry-run` to preview without deleting, or `--force` to skip confirmation.

## Task Tooling

Use `scripts/task` to keep task updates consistent and automatically bump `updated_at`.

- Create a task: `./scripts/task create "Title here"`
- List tasks: `./scripts/task list [--status X] [--has-blockers]`
- Add a log entry: `./scripts/task log TASK-001 "Implemented API pagination"`
- Change status: `./scripts/task status TASK-001 in_review --note "Ready for review"`
- Add blocker: `./scripts/task blocker add TASK-001 "Waiting on backend review"`
- Remove blocker: `./scripts/task blocker remove TASK-001 "Waiting on backend review"`

## Worktree Verification

Run `scripts/verify.sh` to typecheck, lint, and test changes in a worktree before PR.

```bash
# Full verification (typecheck + lint + scoped unit tests)
./scripts/verify.sh <worktree-name>

# Tier 1 only (typecheck + lint)
./scripts/verify.sh <worktree-name> --tier 1

# Quick mode (lint only changed files)
./scripts/verify.sh <worktree-name> --quick
```

### Tiers

| Tier | What | When |
|------|------|------|
| 1 | typecheck + lint | Always (every PR) |
| 2 | + unit tests scoped to changes | Default — when test files exist near changes |
